            "title": "U.S. Benchmark WTI Crude Hits $80 A Barrel",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  By Anthony Harrup </p><br/><p>\n  U.S. benchmark crude oil rose above $80 a barrel Thursday for the first time in more than a year as widening conflict and disruptions in the Middle East raise concerns about global supply. </p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  West Texas Intermediate crude was up 8.6% at $81.09 a barrel in afternoon trade on the New York Mercantile Exchange, its highest level since July of 2024 and above $80 for the first time since January of 2025. International benchmark Brent crude was up 4.7% at $85.21 a barrel. </p><p>\n\n  \"WTI crude oil is suddenly looking like an attractive plan B for global refiners,\" said Robert Yawger, a commodity specialist at Mizuho Securities USA. So far, sky-high tanker rates have stymied U.S. oil exports, but \"if the Persian Gulf continues to shut in tanker traffic, look for the U.S. barrel to become the marginal barrel,\" he added. </p><br/><p>\n  Write to Anthony Harrup at anthony.harrup@wsj.com </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><p>\n\n  03-05-26 1419ET</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/u-s-benchmark-wti-crude-hits-80-a-barrel-ce7e5fdbdc8ef226",
